Section 5: Framework & Methodology

Pro Tip:  Frameworks with catchy names (like "The CIRCLES Method" or "Golden Circle") become industry standards and generate citations.

1. Have you developed a specific process, framework, or methodology for [solving X problem]?
IQS (Integrated Quality Score) - One standardized, explainable score applied to both human and AI interactions. IQS blends rubric-based judgment (tone, empathy, accuracy, resolution, compliance) across both human agents and AI agents. 
2. Can you walk me through your approach step-by-step?
Surface 100% of interactions (human + AI), normalize transcripts/metadata, and auto-tag intents.
Calibrate & Combine: Define the quality rubric, weight criteria by risk, and fuse model scores + human reviews into IQS with confidence intervals.
Outcome-Link: Correlate IQS with KPIs (AFRT, CSAT, churn, refund, recontact, etc) to set thresholds that actually matter.
Remediate upstream: Train agents on skill gaps, retune AI for drift, surface learnings to policy and product where the journey is broken 
Evolve continuously: weekly calibrations, drift detection, re-weighting, exception queues, and executive scorecards.
3. What are the key stages or principles in your methodology?
One standard, all channels: Humans and AI graded by the same rubric.
Judgment over keywords: Criteria target intent, empathy, clarity, and correctness, not just phrase matching.
Explainability by design: Every IQS point is traceable to evidence (turns, snippets, rules).
Continuous calibration: Humans teach AI; AI exposes human blind spots. Both improve.
4. How does your framework differ from traditional approaches?
Orgs are still working out how to blend human and AI scoring, and it’s pretty manual and custom to each team. This framework gives companies a good starting/jumping off point. 
5. Is there a memorable name or acronym for this process?
SCORE
6. What are the common mistakes people make when trying to solve this problem?
Buying tech before truth: Stacking tools without a shared definition of good.
Sampling bias: Making strategy from 2% of interactions and calling it voice of customer.
Policing vs improving: Using QA to catch errors, not to teach judgment or fix upstream causes.
KPI myopia: Optimizing AHT while driving recontacts and silent churn.
Automating bad processes: Speeding up the wrong journey makes the wrong journey cheaper, not better.
No governance: Rubrics drift, AI drifts, policies drift. Without calibration, quality decays.
Ignoring agent experience: Burned-out agents can’t deliver brand-grade judgment; EX is a leading indicator of CX.
One-and-done “listening tours”: Insights that don’t translate into product/policy changes are content, not operations.


Section 6: Industry Predictions & Future Vision

1. Where do you see [industry/category] in 2-3 years?
In the next 2-3 years, CX will move from a function to a source of truth. AI agent companies will seek to become CRMs, as companies realize that support conversations are the cleanest mirror of the business. Customers surface product gaps, process inefficiencies, and brand sentiment before any other dataset can. Leaders over the next 2-3 years won’t just run contact centers, but feedback engines that power decisions across the business. AI will open the doors to operationalized support data - meaning that CX Ops will live next to Strategy in org charts as the strategic layer of the company. 
2. What's about to change in your industry that most people aren't prepared for?
There’s a common belief that AI is going to replace customer support agents by 2030. While yes, some workflows will shift primarily to AI, the big change that will come is the exposing of every inefficiency, every inconsistency, and every assumption happening in CX operations. For decades, support teams could hide behind metrics like AHT and CSAT. Those metrics painted a smoothed-over picture of broken customer journeys. But with the introduction of AI that reveals the truth of each customer journey at scale, there’s nowhere left to hide. We’re entering a world where leadership teams can quantify empathy, clarity, and accuracy – and the uncomfortable truth is that most CX teams aren’t ready to be held to that level of transparency. When the lights turn on, the cracks in process, training, and product will show through. 
3. What should companies be doing now to prepare for what's coming?
Broad strokes - companies should be building CX systems that continuously learn and evolve to constantly improve customer experiences. The next gen of CX orgs will look less like call centers and more like ops-heavy living learning systems. The orgs that come out on top will start (today!!) implementing tools that give them full visibility into their customer interactions at scale, begin generating custom trainings for their support agents based on their individual skill gaps, and stand up VoC programs that turn traditional CSAT reporting into living, breathing feedback loops for product, policy, marketing, and operations teams. 
4. What innovation or shift are you most excited about?
We’re passionate about human and AI agents working together to drive truly great customer experiences, so the shift we’re most excited about is that merging of human judgement with the precision of AI. AI can now listen at an enterprise scale, but it still needs human context to understand what good really is - especially when *good* differs so greatly from org to org. The shift isn’t AI taking over CX - it’s AI learning from humans, and humans improving through AI feedback. 
5. What's the next big problem that needs solving in this space?
The insight to action gap. Most CX leaders don’t truly know what’s broken (as they can only get directional feedback from parsing through 1-2% of customer interactions), and any insights their analysts teams do find die in slide decks, misaligned OKRs, or the six-week delay between identifying a pattern in customer interactions and changing something upstream. The solution is making the insight to action loop instant. This is done when what customers say connects to what QA detects, which determines what trainings change, what product fixes, and what the company learns. 

Section 7: Tactical Advice & Actionable Insights

1. If someone is facing challenges, what's the first thing they should do?
If a CX leader at a growing company is facing challenges scaling their customer support team efficiently, they should look to AI solutions to help solve the problem. This challenge is critically important because fast-growing companies know they need to deliver exceptional customer service experiences to maintain a loyal customer base. The solution is two-sided – CX leaders need to understand their customer problems extremely well, and they need to ensure their staff is prepared to handle those problems extremely well. To understand customer problems well, leaders should look for a solution that allows them to get an immediate picture of the customer interactions happening across every channel (phone, video, live chat, email, etc.). Without AI, this is an incredibly manual process. With AI, this can be done in seconds - giving leaders a perfect view of the pulse of their customers and the problems they’re facing in any given moment. To ensure agents are well prepared to face those problems, leaders should, again, turn to AI. Traditional training methods take a long time to turn around – trainers need to surface training opportunities that are relevant for the broadest group of agents, then create the trainings for the group, then run the trainings. With AI, trainings can be surfaced, created, and assigned in minutes – and are personalized to each agent, rather than made to serve a wide range of agents. 
2. What's a quick win companies can implement immediately?
Start running third-party QA on your BPOs. Doing so will give you a pulse on how certain BPOs compare to others, and where their gaps are. BPOs are a tremendous investment for brands, so ensuring high ROI is imperative. 
3. What tools or resources do you recommend people start with?
Before buying another “customer 360” tool, start by mapping the truth gaps in your current system. Most teams don’t need more dashboards - they need a single, trusted lens on what’s actually happening in customer conversations. That means pulling data from where truth already lives: your CRM, ticketing platform, QA forms, chat logs, and survey comments. The goal is to make qualitative data quantifiable and actionable.
Tools
Conversation intelligence platforms (Gong, Observe.AI, Solidroad) to surface patterns across 100% of interactions — not the 2% humans can manually review.
Quality frameworks and calibration tools to align what “good” means internally before scaling it.
Shared CX insights dashboards that sit next to your business metrics, so experience data becomes part of daily decision-making — not a quarterly slide.
Simple automation + enablement tools (Guru, Notion, or your CRM’s native modules) to close the loop between what’s learned in QA and what’s taught in training.
Resources:
Listen to 50 real customer conversations before you build a strategy deck.
Run a “Voice of the Agent” session. Ask your team what frustrates them most about helping customers. It will tell you more than any NPS survey.
Read works that reframe service as a strategic function: The Effortless Experience, Measure What Matters, and Good Strategy/Bad Strategy are good starting points.
4. What's the biggest mistake you see companies making, and how can they fix it?
Treating customer experience as a department, not an organism. Most companies build CX teams that optimize parts of the journey, like QA scores, handle time, CSAT, CS cost, etc. without understanding that experience is a living system. Every decision made in marketing, product, and operations eventually lands in support’s lap. The symptom (long queues, low CSAT, high churn) isn’t the disease but the lagging indicator of organizational misalignment. CX needs to be reframed as a system of truth, and leaders have an imperative to be connected throughout the organization. It’s reciprocal, too – if CX leaders are plugged in throughout the org, they can both field and have input on decisions being made throughout other orgs that will impact support, as well as pass along real-time data on what’s breaking across the business (bugs, messaging gaps, unmet expectations). The best CX leaders bring that truth to the exec table and make CX the connective tissue between customer reality and company priorities.
5. What's your 'secret weapon' or underutilized tactic that works really well?
An underutilized tactic that works really well (but is objectively not easy to solve without proper tooling) is implementing KPIs around qual, and not quant customer metrics. Every CX org tracks quant metrics (tickets handled, AFRT, AHT, CSAT, NPS, % resolved, etc.) but it’s fairly difficult to track the quality of conversations at scale - especially because most organizations can only QA 1-3% of interactions. But when CX orgs systematically measure how well every human or AI agent aligns with brand standards (tone, empathy, accuracy, etc.), they can unlock compounding improvement that makes a meaningful impact on customers. That’s why our “secret weapon” is operationalizing judgement at scale. Quality isn’t subjective. It can be trained, quantified, and continuously improved. When qual data becomes just as visible as AHT or AFRT, it can change how teams hire, coach, and ultimately shape teams. 
6. What should someone do in their first 30/60/90 days of tackling this problem?
30 days: diagnose reality. Don’t start with a playbook. Listen to real customer conversations. Work with other leaders across the company to create a mutual charter on how CX will interact with other teams to both ingest information around business decisions and share information on customer data. 
60 days: bring on the right tools. Look for AI tools that allow you to fill blind spots in customer experience and take a more proactive approach to support and overall business strategy. AI QA is essential. AI training is a no-brainer. 
90 days: operationalize. Set up ongoing calibrations to continually refine your AI agents. Elevate your leaders to share new learnings from the customer dataset publicly. 

