Section 9: Founder/Expert Journey & Lessons Learned

1. What's been your biggest learning as a [founder/expert] in this space?

Customer Experience (CX) leaders face increasing pressure to uphold exceptional quality standards and maintain high CSAT scores, all while driving down operational costs. They constantly navigate the delicate balance between efficiency and quality. With the rapid advancement of AI, this challenge has only intensified — leaders are now expected to integrate AI solutions extensively across their operations without compromising the customer experience.

2. Tell me about a major failure or setback and what you learned from it.

My first startup, Gradguide, ultimately failed. We built a graduate recruitment platform that connected recent graduates with mentors to help them secure their first roles in the tech industry. I made early fundraising mistakes — raising $2 million on unfavorable terms that gave away 75% of the business. When market conditions tightened in 2021, our lead investor declined to provide additional support and pushed for a sale. Through that experience, I learned the importance of raising capital on fair terms and partnering with long-term investors who share your vision and are committed to supporting the business through both good and challenging times.

3. What advice would you give to someone just starting out in [industry/role]?

My advice to anyone starting a company is to find a co-founder you deeply trust — someone whose strengths complement your own. In my case, I’m not technical, so my co-founder leads on engineering while I focus on go-to-market. That balance has been invaluable. Building a startup is challenging, and having the right partner makes it possible to go further together than you ever could alone.

4. What's something you believed at the start that you've completely changed your mind on?

I used to believe the startup journey would get easier over time, that reaching certain milestones in revenue, team size, or funding would bring stability. In reality, I’ve learned the opposite is true. Each stage brings new and more complex challenges. If you’re still in your role every six months, it’s because you’ve effectively been promoted; the job keeps evolving, and so must you.

5. What's the hardest part of [running this company/doing this work] that people don't see?

The hardest part of my job is managing across multiple time zones. We have an incredible team in Dublin, Ireland, and another in San Francisco. The eight-hour difference means I often wake up to Slack messages at 5 a.m. and work until 9 p.m. most nights. It can be challenging to stay aligned across continents, and in an ideal world, we’d all be in the same room collaborating together.

